title_narrative: The Netherlands Mine Action and Cluster Munitions Programme 2020-2024 - Laos
description_narrative: Under the Mine Action and Cluster Munitions Programme, HI will contribute to enhance human security among communities of Houaphan and Phongsaly provinces in Lao PDR impacted by Explosive Ordnance, and improve their resilience in the face of EO contamination. To that end, the project will adhere to a Comprehensive Approach to Mine Action, integrating Land Release, Risk Education, Community Liaison, Livelihoods, Victim Assistance and support to national mine action authorities.
result_title_narrative: Output 1.1 - Hazard Areas (including minefields) are defined based on evidence and following the CMRS and CWS procedures
Output 1.3 - Risk of EO related death and injury are reduced safely and the feeling of safety is increased through land release activities
Output 1.4 - Communities living in EO contaminated areas improve knowlege, attitudes and practices about EO related risks
Output 1.5 - Communities living in EO contaminated areas improve their socio-economic capacity through the integrated response

Output 2.1 - Tailored community safety committees approached at village level provide durable solutions/dynamics to mitigate the risks of EO accidents ensuring flexible response and conflict sensitivity
Output 2.4 - Survivors, and other most vulnerable beneficiaries, are referred to relevant medical, MHPSS, or rehabilitation services and followed up

result_indicator_period_actual_comment_n: As communicated with the donor, HI experienced in 2021 delays in the signature of the MoU and the accreditation for Mine Action intervention with Lao PDR authorities, that are mandatory to conduct activities. This situation, quite usual in Lao PDR, laster longer than usual in 2021 due to the COVID-19 lockdown which was imposed in Vientiane (from April 2021 onwards) - which made the MoU and accreditation signature particularly long to process. This explains that no target were achieved during the reporting period. The MoU was ultimately signed on July 29th, and the accreditation obtained on August 12th, while COVID-19 lockdown and travel restrictions in Houaphan province were lifted, which now allows HI to implement normally.
As per previously comunicated, operations have resumed after obtention of the accreditation.
Due to COVID-19 outbreak in Houameuang, Houaphan province, Technical Survey (TS) and Area Clearance (AC) tasks were delayed.

April was a long campaign break for Technical Survey (TS) and Area Clearance (AC) activities, as per HI and National Regulatory Authority (NRA) policies. In addition, implementation of TS and AC activities was further challenged due to the start of the rainy season, while some villages were more difficult to access (over 130 kilometers from HI office with difficult road). Finally, a substantial number of UXO were found during the reporting period (over 840 in Namthip village for instance), which takes more time to clear.

This quarter was rainy season in Lao PDR, including heavy rains and flooding in Houaphan province in August and September. This made it difficult to access the more remote target areas which limited project activities. Project team was on campaign break in August.

In 2022, HI recorded its highest ever clearance results since HI land release activities began in 2006 and recorded some of its highest annual number of EO items found. During the reporting quarter, the EOD team progress was slightly hindered by a large amount of vegetation cutting that was required prior to TS/clearance. Usually land owners would support with vegetation cutting, but as it was rice harvesting season, the land owners were not available to support.
In this quarter, the EOD team was able to achieve high results for clearance as a large number of the CHAs were flat, comprising of rice fields.

This reporting quarter included the period of Lao New Year (Pi Mai) during which period the team was on a 3 week campaign break. In spite of the public holidays, the EOD team team was able to achieve good outputs for area clearance as a large number of the CHAs were flat areas with limited metal content.

EOD teams completed activities at the end of August 2023. Some work time was lost in the 9 day working period at the end of July-beginning August due to heavy rain, and some terrain with a high amount of fragmentation and scrap metal in Phongsaly, but good overall progress on clearance.

2020: Through area clearance: 294 cluster munitions and 99 UXO / Through technical survey: 79 cluster munitions / Remote operating vehicle: 7 bombs, 71 cluster munitions, 1 anti-personal mine, 270 UXO // 2021: Remote operating vehicle: 2 anti-personal mine,  1 cluster munition, 15 UXO

As communicated with the donor, HI experienced in 2021 delays in the signature of the MoU and the accreditation for Mine Action intervention with Lao PDR authorities, that are mandatory to conduct activities. This situation, quite usual in Lao PDR, laster longer than usual in 2021 due to the COVID-19 lockdown which was imposed in Vientiane (from April 2021 onwards) - which made the MoU and accreditation signature particularly long to process. This explains that no target were achieved during the reporting period. The MoU was ultimately signed on July 29th, and the accreditation obtained on August 12th, while COVID-19 lockdown and travel restrictions in Houaphan province were lifted, which now allows HI to implement normally.

One of the CHAs worked on during this period had a notable wide variety of different EO, some of them found very deep (37 cm from the surface) and still in excellent condition: a dispenser SUU 30, 19 full rocket 2.75 Inches and a mix of BLU 26 and 3B. This was reported to the UNDP and NRA to inform ongoing discussions around national standards for clearance depth.

In this quarter, EORE was conducted in 1 village in Khoua, Phongsaly province. The MoU for activities in Phongsaly Province was approved in July 2022  and EORE activity started in September as the project team was on campaign break in August. The number of beneficiaries was based on the individuals attending household sessions.

In this quarter, the EORE team were able to conduct inclusive village visits in Phongsaly according to the plan agreed with villages and district authorities. The team delivered EORE in 9 villages in Phongsaly province, conducting community presentations, safety briefings, household EORE sessions and movie nights. The EORE team has now completed 27 villages of the target 39 villages (69%), covering 18 villages in Houaphan province and 9 villages in Phongsaly province. The number of EORE beneficiaries is based on interpersonal EORE delivered during household visits.
In this quarter, the EORE team provided EORE sessions at household level to beneficiaries in 11 villages of Phongsaly province.

Community-based EORE activities were completed in March. EORE activities in this quarter comprised of follow-up visits and refresher trainings where required to Community Focal Points.  HI plans to conduct targeted  EORE in two villages in Houameuang district, Houaphan province in early July based on request from the District Labour Social Welfare Office and an accident that occured in one of the villages on 2nd July.
Community-based EORE activities were completed in March 2023.

First referral and case management to be started and reported on in the next reporting period. Priority of referral will be given to UXO survivors and persons with disabilities for referral to health center and rehabilitation center.

HI could only prioritize and refer a limited number of persons to the rehabilitation centre at the same time or same month, as the centre was over-subscribed with other cases and could not manage the HI caseload. HI referred 11 cases during the quarter. HI expects to refer 30-40 in the next quarter.

In Phongsaly province, the team started to identify and prioritise survivors and persons with disabilities during the comprehensive visits to villages. During the reporting period, the rehabilitation centre in Xiengkhouang was over-subscribed with other cases and was not able to manage the HI caseload. HI referred 27 cases during the quarter and expects to refer 35-45 in the next quarter.

In this quarter, a number of different cases were supported, including prosthesis measurements and fittings. An  eye specialist from Houaphan Hospital assessed 5 cases in Houaphan. Specialists from Xieng Khouang Rehabilitation Centre, however, had limited availability to support HI VA team fin assessing and prioritising cases to refer to the appropriate health care facilities. The limitations of Xieng Khouang rehabilitation center are that it has little health technical staff support - and in addition during this period staff were in technical training period - and  limited space to accommodate EO victims and other persons with disabilities. Moreover, it can cause a delay in referral, as if HI assesses that an individual requires treatment in the capital, Vientiane, due to limited health facilities in the provinces, a recommendation letter is required from the local rehabilitation centre prior to referral (in this case, Xieng Khouang Rehabilitation Centre).

Following the completion of screening and prioritisation of persons with disabilities in the previous quarter, the VA team was able to support 82 individuals with referral to available services between April - June.

In this quarter, there were 8 cases referred to health care services. There continued to be delays and issues with doctors and rehabilitation centre having availability to see patients referred by HI.
